description:
This is an open-source code written in Python for implementing continuous wavelet transform (CWT) to detect the lysosome trajectory segments corresponding to active versus passive motion.&nbsp; 

 The initial version of this code was published by Polev et al.,  Cells   11 , 270 (2022). 

 The updated version of the code/software uploaded here is described in reference:&nbsp; 

 Kandere-Grzybowska, K., Polev, K., Kolygina, D.V., Grzybowski, B.A. (2023). Protocol and Software for Automated Detection of Lysosome Active &ldquo;Runs&rdquo; and &ldquo;Flights&rdquo; with Wavelet Transform Approach. In: Kalyuzhny, A.E. (eds) Signal Transduction Immunohistochemistry. Methods in Molecular Biology, vol 2593. Humana, New York, NY. https://doi.org/10.1007/978-1-0716-2811-9_11 

 If you find this code/ software useful , please cite these references.&nbsp; 

 The key important updates include compatibility with the Fiji/ TrackMate data files (with xy trajectory data)&nbsp;and an&nbsp;intuitive graphical user interface (GUI) with interactive track browser.&nbsp;&nbsp;The computing of CWT coefficients for all trajectories, assignment of active vs. passive motion,&nbsp;&nbsp;plotting of complementary cumulative distribution functions, model comparisons (lognormal, power law, truncated power law, stretched exponential, exponential), Akaike weight analysis, and extraction of the basic aggregate parameters of lysosome dynamics (run/flight length, run/flight duration, diffusion coefficient, exponent alpha, percentage of time spent in active transport) are performed automatically. 

 In this upload, we also include an example of properly formatted xy trajectory data file(s) in .csv format (obtained by tracking Lysotracker Red-labeled organelles with the TrackMate plugin). Representative&nbsp; movie showing the dynamics of Lysotracker-labeled organelles in HT1080 fibrosarcoma cells&nbsp;is&nbsp;also included.

